@node About "About Locate"

	@{b}ABOUT LOCATE@{ub}

Locate© is one amongst a million Address Book programs littered throughout the computer world (and probably the most common thing found in waste disposal units around the galaxy). There are enough of them around in varied forms so that you can usually find one that suites your own personal needs. I however could not find one that had all the things I needed and suited my philosophy in program design, so I wrote my own. Here is my input to the wonderful world of Address Book programs 8).

Locate functions mainly as an Address lister but it can be altered slightly to lend itself into other areas. Read the entire document to find out what makes this one different from the rest.

Locate is a MUI (Magic User Interface) application. This means you need the MUI files/library to use the Locate. I chose to develop using MUI because of its flexibility and easy of use, both for the user and programmer. It allows a fairly flexible environment for both the programmer and the user. MUI is hopefully the direction of the future. Unfortunately, a lot of people misunderstand or fail to realise how powerful MUI really is. MUI is available as a reduced product on the Public Domain, but if you wish to have full control, and support a great product that supports the continuing life of the Amiga, then @{"register" link Everyday:Introduction.guide/MUI_Register} for the full version.

Locate© is classified Giftware. See @{"License & Disclaimer" link Everyday:Introduction.guide/License}.

Mathew Wilson

	Contact me at:
	
	Box 6022, Halifax Street Post Office
	Adelaide SA, 5000
	AUSTRALIA

	EMail: mind@inorbit.com
	WWW:   http:www.adam.com.au/~mwilson/
@endnode

@node Using "Using Locate."

	@{b}USING LOCATE@{ub}

Locate has been designed specifically for ease of use and to provide a variety of useful functions to help manage small lists. It is not meant to be a fully functional database system; it really doesn't come close at all.

The program is layed out with a standard MUI list and all the fields for an Address listed below it. The reason for laying out all the field below is that you can easily see and edit data for entry quickly. Of course this is limiting in the sense that you may only edit one entry at a time but this has been done for speed only and if you like editing a billion entries at once then I'm sure there is one out there that does. The other disadvantage is the height of the window required.

Although Locate may not necessarily be used as an address lister, we shall refer to an individual entry as a collection of fields making an "Address".

The program uses standard tooltypes to store its configuration settings. These are parameters set in the programs/caller's icon that the program looks for at run-time. The settings are generally global and all Address information is saved to a separate file. It is important to realise the difference between saving file-settings and saving Address lists!
@endnode

@node CreateAddress "Creating an Address Entry."

	@{b}CREATING AND ADDRESS ENTRY@{ub}

As previously mentioned in the introduction, some programs open edit windows when you create an entry and add the entry if you accept the new data. Locate works slightly differently to help you speed up data entry and create a system that's functional and easy to use.

This poses some questions for the new user, for example;
 "Without an accept button, how does the program actually know when to add an Address to the list?"

The answer to this is very simple. Locate requires that a new Address contain something in either or both of the first two fields: Last Name and First Name. Locate will add the current Address into the list whenever this requirement is met.

To create a new entry all you must do is:
· Deselect anything in the main list, which in turn clears the Address fields below the list. This can be done by either clicking the New button or pressing the DELETE key form the keyboard (no gadget selected). In the first case, selected or active entries in the list are deselected, the data fields below are cleared and the cursor appears in the first field string gadget. The latter will not activate the Last Name gadget. You will now be in ADD mode.

In other words, when nothing is selected in the list, the Address data fields should logically be showing no data from the list, as they indicate the currently active entry. So usually whenever you see that the Address fields are ALL blank then you know you're in ADD mode.

· Start entering data and when Locate recognises that the NEW Address criteria are met then it will insert the current data into the list and THEN the entry will appear activated in the list. This now indicates that you are NOT in ADD mode but are in EDIT mode. To edit the entry all you must do is activate it in the list (if it isn't already), change the data and press return to accept it.

NOTE: Locate requires that you @{bg highlight}@{b}** MUST **@{ub}@{bg background} press RETURN after entering data into anyone on the Address data fields. Failure to do this @{b}WILL@{ub} result in the loss of this data! Pressing return means that you are accepting the data. This is a side-effect of the method of data entry used.

There are short cut keys for each of the fields. Press the number 1 to 7 that corresponds with the ordering of the fields.
@endnode

@node AddressData "What an Address Consists Of."

	@{b}WHAT AN ADDRESS CONSISTS OF@{ub}

An Address must consist of either or both the first two fields. For the sake of clarity we shall refer to the fields with their default names as they can be @{"renamed" link FieldsWindow} to suit the language or situation.

@{b}1. Last Name@{ub}

This field may contain up to 128 alpha/numeric characters.
Editing this field in ADD mode will cause the current Address data be inserted into the list as a new entry.
In EDIT mode the entry will be resorted in the list.

@{b}2. First Name@{ub}

This field may contain up to 128 alpha/numeric characters.
Editing this field in ADD mode will cause the current Address data be inserted into the list as a new entry.
In EDIT mode the entry will be resorted in the list.

@{b}3. Street@{ub}

This field may contain up to 128 alpha/numeric characters.

@{b}4. Suburb@{ub}

This field may contain up to 128 alpha/numeric characters.

@{b}5. Post Code@{ub}

This field may contain up to 20 numeric characters.

@{b}6. Phone@{ub}

This Popstring gadget contains a mini-list of phone-number strings. Currently you can have up to 4 entries in this gadget. Just select the Popup gadget to the right of the string and a standard list of phone numbers will appear. If you are unfamiliar with MUI-PopString gadgets then please read the MUI documentation.

The pop-list may be left open all the time if you wish. This enables you to see the entries as you scroll through entries in the main Address list. If you are ADD mode then the list will default to four standard strings - "Home:", "Fax:", "Work:" and "Email:". You may use these as standard guides to your data entry or you may use your own but it shows that it's a good idea to pre-fix phone numbers with an ID of some sort.

The phone strings may contain up to 60 alpha/numeric characters.

Refer to @{"Dialing numbers" link Dialing} for a full description of the "Dial" button.

@{b}7.Notes:@{ub}

This field may contain up to 128 alpha/numeric characters.

The button marked @{b}View@{ub} is used for viewing and editing @{"external data files" link ExternalData} for each individual entry.
@endnode

@node AddressList "Using the Address List."

	@{b}USING THE ADDRESS LIST@{ub}

The main list can be used as like any standard MUI List.

You can remove entry(s) with the Remove button below the list.
Entries can be duplicated with the Copy button.

To deselect any active or highlighted entries from the list just press the DELETE key on the keyboard.

You may even change the display/order of items in the list by altering the "List Format:", described in @{"Configuration" link ConfigWindow}.

At the top of the Main Window where the window title is, you will see some extra information displayed. It will either display "No Entries" or some numbers in the form "#:# of # (#) xxxx". This displays the number of the active entry, the number of selected entries,  total Address entries (for a description of the difference between Active and Selected entries, see your MUI documentation), the unique ID number for the Active entry and the name of the currently loaded file.

In addition to the normal loading methods, you may drag-and-drop icons onto the Main List or its app-icon (when iconified). This is performed via a User-Configurable @{"ARexx Script" link DropScript}.
@endnode

@node DropScript "Drag and Drop Script"

	@{b}APPLICATION WINDOW/ICON - DROP SCRIPT@{ub}

When an Icon is dropped onto the Locate Main List an ARexx script named 'Locate_DropObj.rexx' is called with its first argument being the name of the File that was dropped. You must indicate where this script is by manually setting the tooltype 'DROP_SCRIPT' in the Locate program icon.

This method enables the user to specify what exactly is to be done with files that are dropped onto Locate. The normal outcome of such an event would be to attempt to load the file. This is the standard function of the default script that is installed with Locate, but you may of course alter this to suit your own needs.

Like all scripts that are run from Locate, the invoked script has its host address set to the Locate port automatically. This way the script will know exactly who to send its messages to (see example).
@endnode

@node ExternalDataWindow "Using External Information Files."

	@{b}USING EXTERNAL INFORMATION FILES@{ub}

Sometimes you need to store an unknown amount of data about a particular person. In a business situation this data could be contact dates and enquiries etc. This sort of data does not need to be loaded into memory at all times but you need to be able to access it quickly.

Locate's external data files are a solution to this problem. They are information files that are stored in a directory, ready to be called up when needed.

In the main window next to the Notes data field is the View button. When you click on this button the Note View Window opens. Locate will now look for an information data file that belongs to the current entry selected. If it is found then its contents will be displayed in this window.

You may leave this window open. If you do then Locate will look for an information file everytime you select and entry in the main list. This may slow things down more than usual because Locate is accessing the disk and attempting to load data everytime you select a new entry. So you have the option of leaving the window opened or closed.

The Edit button in the Notes View Window enables you to create or alter data in the information file(s). Locate will call an external editor to edit this data. You may instruct Locate to use your favourite editor in the @{"Configuration" link ConfigWindow}. If the editor doesn't detatch itself from the current process then Locate will wait till you finished editing and then update the new information in the Notes View Window. Locate waits for the editor to return, but some editors detatch themselves from the current process and return control. This mean that Locate will not know when to update the Notes View Window. You can easily update it by reselecting the entry in the main list.

This window uses Mark Thomas' @{"TextField.gadget" link TextField_Commands.guide/Main} class so you may edit the External Note Data file sirect from this window and use the Save button to keep the changes.

Locate will look for the information files in a particular drawer. The location of this drawer is user-configurable and is saved with the Address file. See @{"Configuration" link ConfigWindow}.

Locate provides a method for determining at a glance whether or not an Address has any external information notes. You can do this be setting the @{"List Format" link ConfigWindow} option with column 7 (col=7) showing. Locate will fill this column with either a " ", ".", "-" or "*" meaning:

   ' ' (Blank) - Locate has not searched for an external notes data file for this entry.

   '.' - Locate has looked and not found a found the data file for this entry.

   '-' - A data file exists for this entry but it is empty

   '*' - A data file exists for this entry and it contains information.

To scan for information files you can use the Scan Notes option found under Functions menu. Alternatively, if you have column 7 showing as a default in your List Format then you might like Locate to scan for data files every time it loads the Address List. This can be accomplished with the Scan Notes option in the @{"Configuration" link ConfigWindow}.
@endnode

@node Searching "Searching the List."

	@{b}SEARCHING THE LIST@{ub}

Below the Address list is a string gadget labeled Search.  Just type some text in here, press return and Locate will search the list for a matching entry. It will start searching straight after the Active entry or from the top if nothing is Activated in the list.If you want to deactivate the list just press DELETE from the keyboard or click on the New button.

Searching is performed using standard AmigaDOS pattern matching (see you AmigaDOS manual) so make sure you enter the search string correctly!

e.g. a search string of "Ami" will NOT match "Amiga" because it is looking for an exact length match. Instead you would type "Ami#?" to match "Amiga". (Note: Some programs patch "#?" to allow you to use "*" instead.)

The parameters for the search are set in the @{"Configuration" link ConfigWindow}.
@endnode

@node Dialing "Using the Dialler"

	@{b}USING THE DIALLER@{ub}

Locate has a built in dialler attached to the phone data field. This means that if you have a modem you can use Locate to dial numbers directly from the Address list.

Just activate the entry from the list you would like to dial and select the correct phone number from the phone lister and press the Dial button. A requester stating what number is being dialed will appear. It will also ask you to close the requester (press return) when you have picked up the phone.

If you have your modem speaker turned on you should hear the modem dialing. When you hear the standard dial tone, you may pick up the phone and close the requester to hangup the modem.

A pre-dial string may be sent to the modem. This is set in the @{"Configuration" link Config_GeneralDialler}.
If a pre-dial string exists then the Dialler will wait 2 seconds until dialling the actual number. This allows for things such as an ATZ in the pre-dial string to complete. 

The Dialler works on a "device level". You can set the driver and and unit number in the @{"Configuration" link Config_GeneralDialler}.

@{b}Dialler Stripping@{ub}

Some stripping of characters is performed on the dial string so as not to confuse the modem. If you had a string - 'Phone: 8276-1902,9,9,9', the prefix name 'Phone:', space and '-' character would have to be removed.

Locate performs stripping like this:

· Scan the string from left to right and find the first instance of a legal character.
   A legal character can be a numerical character or a '&', '@', '!', ',' , ';' or '^'. If it finds a capital A, then it will check to see if a capital T follows it, as this would most likely be an AT command for the modem. Once a legal character is found then the first stage of stripping stops.
· Now it will continue to strip ONLY '-' or ' ' (space) characters from the string.

So in our example we would end up with '82761902,9,9,9'.

This means that if an extraneous text is to be included in the Dial string then it is a good idea to place it at the beginning or your modem may complain.
@endnode

@node ConfigWindow "The Configuration Window."

	@{b}THE CONFIGURATION WINDOW@{ub}

This window contains three pages of settings and defaults for Locate. Only those in the group labeled Defaults get saved as the configuration via tooltypes in the program icon.

	@{"  " link Config_Search}  Search Parameters
	@{"  " link Config_File}  File Settings
	@{"  " link Config_General}  General Settings (saved as ToolTypes in program's icon)

A tooltype called STARTUP_SCRIPT exists that enables you to specify an ARexx script that you would like executed at run-time.
@endnode

@node Config_Search "The Configuration Window"

	@{b}SEARCH PARAMETERS@{ub}

@{b}Case Sensitivity: @{ub}

This controls the case sensitivity of list @{"searching" link Searching}. If you turn this on then Locate will only find entries that exactly match the case of the search string.


@{b}Fields:@{ub}

This cycle gadget allows you to select which Address fields are included when performing a search.
@endnode

@node Config_File "The Configuration Window"

	@{b}FILE SETTINGS@{ub}

@{b}Password:@{ub}

Locate enables you to set password protection on an Address list so that a password must be entered correctly before the entire file can be loaded. The password may be up to 30 characters long. To enter a password just activate the string gadget, type the password and then press return. Now the gadget will clear and become active again. It is now waiting for you to verify the new password by re-typing it. Once this is accomplishes successfully, the password will be displayed in a hidden form.

Now just save the current Address file in the standard way from the pull down menus. Everytime the file is loaded you will be required to re-type this password. You get two tries. If you fail then the file will NOT be loaded.

@{b}File Encryption:@{ub} {On, Off}

Password protection wouldn't be too much use if you could still read the Address file in a standard text viewer. This option will Encrypt the Address file upon saving and Decrypt it when loaded successfully. With this option, no-one will be able to read the file from a text viewer. So don't forget your password or you'll never be able to either 8).

@{b}Field Names:@{ub}

This button allows you to alter the @{"field names" link FieldsWindow}.

@{b}List Format:@{ub} default

This is a simple string gadget that enables you to change the format of the Address list. This is a standard feature of MUI lists and you can do things like change the order of the columns.

The default list display is - Last Name, First Name

You could change this to - First Name, Street by entering "col=1, col=2" in the List Format gadget. "col" stands for Column and represents the columns of the default display above. Entering just "," (the default) means to just use the default columns. The "," (comma) represents the spacer between each column.

The columns are assigned as follows: (using the default english @{"field names" link FieldsWindow})

	0 = Last Name
	1 = First Name
	2 = Street
	3 = Suburb
	4 = Post Code
	5 = Phone entry 1
	6 = Notes String
	7 = External Notes Info.

@{b}Notes Dir:@{ub}

This pop-drawer gadget lets you choose the source drawer that Locate will look in for the external information files. This drawer must be set if you are to use external information files.

@{b}Scan Notes:@{ub}

If you are using column 7 (External Information @{"Files" link ExternalData} Info) then this option will enable scanning the files upon loading of an Address list. This way 'Column 7' will immediately indicate if an entry has an external  data file.

@{b}Justify Notes@{ub} ** TEMPORARILY REMOVED v1.30 **

This switch controls justification in the Extern Notes Window. If selected, the notes will be fully-flushed, otherwise they will flushed left.
@endnode

@node Config_General "The Configuration Window"

	@{b}GENERAL CONFIGURATION@{ub}
	
These settings contained within this page are saved as Icon ToolTypes in the program's icon.
	
	@{"Options" link Config_GeneralOptions}
	@{"Dialler" link Config_GeneralDialler}

@endnode

@node Config_GeneralOptions "The Configuration Window"

	@{b}GENERAL OPTIONS@{ub}

@{b}Default File:@{ub}

This pop-file gadget enables you to set a default file that will be loaded everytime Locate is run from Workbench. This is a useful option considering most people only have one Address list. So don't forget to set it or things could get really boring.

If you hold down the left mouse button after running Locate, it will not load the default file, but you have to be quick!

@{b}Note Editor:@{ub}

This pop-file gadget lets you select the text editor of your choice for editing data in the information files. It basically tries to execute the given file and gives the relevant External Note Data File as an argument. You could call an ARexx script with 'c:rx <editor>'. The ideal Text Editor would be one that has REAL word wrap and doesn't fake it with those annoying carriage-returns. If anyone finds one, please let me know 8). (such  a basic thing)

@{b}Confirm Remove:@{ub} {On, Off}

This check mark gadget enables user-confirmation requests when removing entries from the list.

@{b}Iconify Mode:@{ub} {On, Off}

If you place Locate in your WBStartup drawer then the program will load everytime you reboot. In such case you would most likely have Locate start Iconified. This can be accomplished by altering the MUI settings for the program. Normally Locate will quit when you close its Main Window. By turning ON the Iconify Mode option you can have Locate Iconify instead of quiting. To quit the program you can use the Quit option from the Project pull-down menu.

The Load and Save buttons affect these settings only.
@endnode

@node Config_GeneralDialler "The Configuration Window"

	@{b}DIALLER SETTINGS@{ub}

@{b}Device:@{ub}

The Dialler function works in a "device level" context. This allows it to work with a variety of different hardware configurations. If you are using the standard serial port for the Amiga then you'll want the dialler to use the "serial.device". If you have a multi-port serial card then you'll want to type the name of the device driver in this gadget. You may enter the AmigaDOS path of the driver as well but if it resides in DEVS: then you can leave the path out. Although AmigaDOS files names are not case-sensitive, this device name is. So type the name exactly, e.g. "serial.device" NOT "Serial.device".

@{b}Unit:@{ub}

This refers to the unit number of the device. If you have a multi-port serial card, this is the number of the port you want to access. Numbers range from 0 upwards.

@{b}Pre-Dial:@{ub}

When using the @{"Dial" link Dialing} function you may want to send a string to the modem first. This gadget represents this optional string.
@endnode

@node Merging "Merge Loading an Address File."

	@{b}MERGE-LOADING AN ADDRESS FILE@{ub}

This option is enable from the Project menu.

It allows you to merge another standard Locate Address file into the current list. The file you select to Merge Load will NOT be affected, only the currently loaded list will be changed.

Whenever it finds an entry in the merge file that has the same Last and First Names as an entry in the current list it will open a requester displaying the information and ask you what you would like to do with it.

@{b}Add:@{ub}

Adds this new entry into the list. It will NOT replace the matching entry in the currently loaded list.

@{b}Replace:@{ub}

Replace the entry in the currently loaded list with the entry found in the Merge file.

@{b}Skip:@{ub}

Skips over the entry found in the Merge file.

@{b}Abort:@{ub}

Abort the Merge procedure all-together.
@endnode

@node Importing "Importing ASCII files"

	@{b}IMPORTING ASCII TEXT FILES@{ub}

It is possible to import a certain type of structured ASCII file into Locate. If you have a list setup in another program and wish to import it into Locate you may use this function found in the Project menu.

To successfully import an ASCII file, Locate expects it to be in the following format:

· A RETURN (ASCII 13) or LINEFEED (ASCII 10) character terminates a single line in the ASCII file.
· Each line will be interpreted as a single record to be imported.
· The line will be formatted such that it contains individual pieces of data separated by TAB (ASCII 9) characters.

As each line in the file is interpreted by Locate, it fills out an Address entry using this data. When it comes to the end of the line it checks to see if there is @{"enough data" link AddressData} to create a new entry. If there is, then it will insert this new entry into the list, otherwise this information will be discarded and the next line read from the input file.

The ASCII format that Locate expects is exactly the same as the output when @{"printing" link Printing} in Column format. So you could export using that function.

At the moment Locate will not check the format or contents of the file before it imports it. So please be certain that it is of the correct type.
@endnode

@node Printing "Printing the Address List."

	@{b}PRINTING THE ADDRESS LIST@{ub}

Printing can be enabled in the Project menu.

A window with various features will appear.

@{b}Output:@{ub}

This string gadget allows you to select the destination for all print output. The default is "PRT:" representing the preferences setup Printer.device. If you wish the output to be placed directly into a disk file then just type its path and file name.

@{b}Header:@{ub}

The header string you would like to appear at the top of the output.

@{b}Print:@{ub}

This cycle gadget selects what entries are to be printed.  "Selected" will print only entries that are selected in the list and "All" will print all entries.

@{b}Perspective:@{ub}

This cycle gadget selects either Vertical or Horizontal" printing.

Vertical prints all data for an individual entry @{i}down@{ui} the page.
Horizontal prints all data for an individual entry @{i}across@{ui} the page. This appears as columns. Each column is separated with TAB characters. The latter method is probably more useful for exporting into another program or even a word processor where you can format the columns.

@{b}Print Field Names:@{ub}

This option will cause the names of each field to be printed. If you have Vertical perspective selected then the fields will be printed on the left of each piece of data as it in printed successively down the page. With Horizontal perspective selected then the field names will appear as column titles.

@{b}Field Activation Check-Mark Gadgets:@{ub}

There is a check-mark gadget for each Address field. You may turn them on and off individually for the printing process. 
@endnode

@node FieldsWindow "Altering the Field Names."

	@{b}ALTERING THE ADDRESS FIELD NAMES@{ub}

You may give different descriptions to the Address fields within Locate. This enables you to tailor a Locate file for a specific purpose. If you live in America you may just want to change the field name "Post Code:" to "ZIP:". It's all up to you.

The defaults for the english language are:

	*1 - Last Name:
	*2 - First Name:
	 3 - Street:
	 4 - Suburb:
	 5 - Post Code:
	 6 - Phone:
	 7 - Notes:

* However, it is important to realise that the first two fields are the SORT fields. This means that Locate uses these two fields to keep an entry sorted alphabetically in the list. The first field has the greatest priority while the second has the least. This means that the first field is used for sorting and the second field is examined only if two of the first fields match exactly.
@endnode

@node Future "In the Future..."

	@{b}MAYBE IN THE FUTURE ...@{ub}

- I keep having these dreams where I completely re-write Locate from scratch making it more configurable. Unfortunately I forget the dreams when I wake up and I've lost a bit of zeal for reconstructional surgery after the energy spent of On-Time v2.0. Locate does all I want at the moment anyway. There are surely as many Address Book programs in this world as there are texture mapping games on the PC, so pick the one that suites you.
- Any suggestions?

@endnode

@node History "History"

· @{b}v1.50@{ub} - Sixth Release (1st April 1997)

   @{fg highlight}Miscellaneous@{fg text}
   - 100% recompiled with SAS/C 6.57.
   
   @{fg highlight}ARexx@{fg text}
   - Sending Mechansism re-writen. Number of ARexx messages executing at once is now unlimited.
   - Run-time dynamically installable User ARexx @{"Menus" link ARexxScripts}.
   - @{"RX" link RX_RX} Redefined.
   
   @{fg highlight}Obsolete Tooltypes@{fg text}
   - AREXX_SCRIPT_1, AREXX_SCRIPT_2, AREXX_SCRIPT_3, AREXX_SCRIPT_4

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.40@{ub} - Fifth Release (9th December 1996)

   - The Dialler used to strip everything that was non-numerical. This meant that any commas ',' or other Modem recognised symbols were removed. Refer to the @{"Dialler" link Dialing} documentation for an update on stripping. Alteration suggested by Michael Martin.
   - Improved Dialler error alerts.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.30@{ub} - Fourth Release (31st August 1996)

   - Due to popular demand, the Locate dial function has been re-written for "device level" access. You may now specify a device name and unit number in the Configuration.
   - Finally, Finally, Finally at long last I got around to using Mark Thomas' TextField.gadget in the External Note Window. Sorry I took so long 8). This has meant the temporary removal of the "Notes Justify:' option from the File Configuration because this class does not allow flush justification.
   - Removed the unecessary scroller bar from the Phone PopList.
   - Whenever the Password Window appears and the Note Window is open the later window will be closed before hand. Opening the Password Window while the Note Window was opened was causing a delayed crash for some bizzare reason.
   - No longer uses LowLevel.library.
   - Renamed "Window Quit:" option to "Iconify Mode:" (reversed effect) for clarity and consistency.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.20@{ub} - Third Release (8th June 1996)

   - Program is now completely cataloged. Hmm, I enjoyed doing that 8).
   - Added Copy function instead of using ARexx.
   - PutField ARexx command renamed to SetField.
   - Added Requester ARexx command.
   - Renamed ARexx command 'Load' to 'Open' for consistency.
   - Bit of recoding here and there.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.10@{ub} - Second Release (27th March 1996)

   - Program ripped to pieces and thrown back together again in an Object Oriented sense. This didn't do much to change the program other than to make it larger 8).
   - Fixed numerous criminal activities (Enforcer hits).
   - Renamed ARexx command 'View' to 'NoteView' and 'Scan' to 'NoteScan' as this seems a little more logical.
   - Altered template for ARexx command @{"GetField" link RX_GetField} from 'NUMBER/N' to 'ENTRY/N/K,NUMBER/N'
   - Inserted 'Edit' menu and shifted 'Clear' items here to keep things a little more consistent with the other EO programs and also a lot more logical. Something that a lot of other programmers should think about!
   - Added 'Select' menus to 'Edit' Menu.
   - Fixed 'ImportASCII' function. It was not importing phone entries 2-4.
   - Fixed a few minor things.
   - Added a quick Startup stack check.
   - Fixed CON: de-allocation for ARexx messages.
   - Added 'DROP_SCRIPT' icon tooltype.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.0@{ub} - Original Release (8th February 1996)

@endnode

@remark ************************************************************
@remark                   ARexx Commands Start Here
@remark ************************************************************

@node ARexxScripts

	@{b}USER-CONFIGURABLE AREXX SCRIPTS@{ub}

Locate allows you to execute external ARexx scripts from within the program. In which case you must have ARexx operational on your system (refer Amiga manuals). Locate will not execute the scripts itself but tell ARexx to perform the scripts (standard procedure). The essential difference is that the default Host Port for the script will be Locate.x.

In the ARexx pull-down menu you will find the following items.

@{b}Run New Script...@{ub}

A file requester will open. Select an ARexx script and close the requester. The file will be executed as an ARexx script.

@{b}Run Last Script@{ub}

This calls the script previously invoked with the 'Run New Script' menu command. If no ARexx script exists then a file requester will open.

@{b}User Definable ARexx Menus@{ub}

Below these two menu items you may install pre-defined ARexx scripts with individual menu-shortcuts. At run-time Locate looks for the file 'Everyday:Locate.ARexxMenu' and scans it for names of scripts to install in the menu. Refer to instructions contained within the file.
@endnode

@node ARexxCommands "ARexx Commands"

	@{b}AREXX COMMAND SET@{ub}

Apart from the built in MUI ARexx commands (see MUI documentation) there are many others to help you control Locate.
The commands return their result in the ARexx RESULT variable. Any errors will be reported in the RC variable (0 = success, any other value indicates an error).

The ARexx port is LOCATE.<x> where <x> is the number of the current program (like most MUI applications, you may run Locate more than once).

You can install user-defined @{"ARexx Menu scripts" link ARexxScripts} for easy reference as well.

@{fg highlight}- A -@{fg text}
@{"About"          link RX_About}          (NO ARGS)
@{"Active"         link RX_Active}         ENTRY/N,NOACTIVE/S

@{fg highlight}- C -@{fg text}
@{"ClearAll"       link RX_ClearAll}       (NO ARGS)
@{"ClearList"      link RX_ClearList}      (NO ARGS)
@{"Copy"           link RX_Copy}           ENTRY/S

@{fg highlight}- D -@{fg text}
@{"Dial"           link RX_Dial}           NUMBER,ACTIVE/S

@{fg highlight}- G -@{fg text}
@{"GetActive"      link RX_GetActive}      (NO ARGS)
@{"GetEntries"     link RX_GetEntries}     (NO ARGS)
@{"GetExtNoteDir"  link RX_GetExtNoteDir}  (NO ARGS)
@{"GetExtNoteName" link RX_GetExtNoteName} (NO ARGS)
@{"GetField"       link RX_GetField}       ENTRY/N/K,NUMBER/N
@{"GetFileName"    link RX_GetFileName}    (NO ARGS)
@{"GetSelect"      link RX_GetSelect}      ACTIVE/S

@{fg highlight}- L -@{fg text}
@{"ListFormat"     link RX_ListFormat}     FORMAT/F

@{fg highlight}- N -@{fg text}
@{"NoteDelete"     link RX_NoteDelete}     (NO ARGS)
@{"NoteEdit"       link RX_NoteEdit}       (NO ARGS)
@{"NoteExamine"    link RX_NoteExamine}    (NO ARGS)
@{"NoteScan"       link RX_NoteScan}       (NO ARGS)
@{"NoteView"       link RX_NoteView}       STATE/N

@{fg highlight}- O -@{fg text}
@{"Open"           link RX_Open}           FILE,MERGE/S

@{fg highlight}- P -@{fg text}
@{"PhoneActive"    link RX_PhoneActive}    ENTRY/N

@{fg highlight}- R -@{fg text}
@{"Remove"         link RX_Remove}         ACTIVE/S
@{"Requester"      link RX_Requester}      TITLE/K,BUTTON/K,MESSAGE/F
@{"RX"             link RX_RX}             FILE

@{fg highlight}- S -@{fg text}
@{"Save"           link RX_Save}           (NO ARGS)
@{"SaveAs"         link RX_SaveAs}         FILE,REQUEST/S
@{"Search"         link RX_Search}         CASESENS/S,FIELD/N/K,STRING/F/A
@{"Select"         link RX_Select}         ENTRY/N,NOSELECT/S,ALL/S
@{"SetField"       link RX_SetField}       NUMBER/N,VALUE/F/A
@endnode

@node RX_About

@{b}About@{ub}

Purpose: Displays the About requester.

Syntax : About (no parameters)
 
Example: about
@endnode

@node RX_Active

@{b}Active@{ub}

Purpose: Set the active entry in the list. The data fields will be updated as well.

Syntax : Active ENTRY/N,NOACTIVE/S

ENTRY/N    - The number of the entry.
NOACTIVE/S - Flag to de-activate the list (eg. no entry active). All data fields will be cleared.

Example: active 5
@endnode

@node RX_ClearAll

@{b}ClearAll@{ub}

Purpose: Removes all entries from the current list and resets field names to their defaults.

Syntax : ClearAll (no parameters)
 
Example: clearall
@endnode

@node RX_ClearList

@{b}ClearList@{ub}

Purpose: Remove all entries from the current list.

Syntax : ClearList (no parameters)

Example: clearlist
@endnode

@node RX_Copy

@{b}Copy@{ub}

Purpose: To make an exact duplicate of an existing entry.

Syntax : ENTRY/N

ENTRY/N  - Number of the entry in the list (1 to Entries) to copy. If you do not specify ENTRY then the current Active entry will be used.

Example: copy
         copy 2
@endnode

@node RX_Dial

@{b}Dial@{ub}

Purpose: @{"Dial" link Dialing} a telephone number using the SER: device.

Syntax : Dial NUMBER,ACTIVE/S

NUMBER   - The telephone number as a string of characters. (Non numeric characters will be stripped).
ACTIVE/S - Flag to dial the number from the currently active entry in the list.
 
Example: dial active
@endnode

@node RX_GetActive

@{b}GetActive@{ub}

Purpose: Return the number of the currently active entry in the list.

Syntax : GetActive (no parameters)
 
Example: getactive
         active = result
@endnode

@node RX_GetEntries

@{b}GetEntries@{ub}

Purpose: Return the current number of entries in the list.

Syntax : GetEntries (no parameters)
 
Example: getentries
         entries = result
@endnode

@node RX_GetExtNoteDir

@{b}GetExtNoteDir@{ub}

Purpose: Return the current External Note Directory path name.

Syntax : GetNoteDir (no parameters)
 
Example: getextnotedir
         path = result
@endnode

@node RX_GetExtNoteName

@{b}GetExtNoteName@{ub}

Purpose: Every entry that exists in Locate's Main List has its own unique identification number. This number *never* changes. Locate uses this number in conjunction with a standard format to name all its External Note Data Files.
         The format is: Text#.ln (where # is the ID number).
         There may be instances where you would like to know what the External Note file name for the currently Active entry is. This ARexx command will return the string.

Syntax : GetNoteName (no parameters)
 
Example: getextnotename
         filename = result
@endnode

@node RX_GetField

@{b}GetField@{ub}

Purpose: Return the contents of a data field from a specific entry or the active entry in the list.

Syntax : GetField ENTRY/N/K,NUMBER/N

ENTRY/N/K - Number of the entry in the list (1 to Entries) to get info on. If you do not specify ENTRY then the current Active entry will be used.
NUMBER/N  - The number of the field to return.

The following are the field numbers (using the default names for the fields):

  1 - Last Name
  2 - First Name
  3 - Street
  4 - Suburb
  5 - Post Code
  6 - Phone (entry 1)
  7 - Phone (entry 2)
  8 - Phone (entry 3)
  9 - Phone (entry 4)
 10 - Notes

Example: getfield 2 /* get field number 2 of the active entry in the list */
         firstname = result
         
         getfield entry 5 2 /* get field number 2 of list entry 5 */
         firstname = result
@endnode

@node RX_GetFileName

@{b}GetFileName@{ub}

Purpose: Return the filename of the current list.

Syntax : GetFileName (no parameters)
 
Example: getfilename
         file = result
@endnode

@node RX_GetSelect

@{b}GetSelect@{ub}

Purpose: Return selection state of and entry or the entire list.

Syntax : Select ACTIVE/S

ACTIVE/S - Return the state of the currently active entry in the list.
           (0 = not selected, 1 = selected)
           
         Without the ACTIVE switch this function will return the number of selected entries in the list.

Example: getselect active
         getselect
@endnode

@node RX_ListFormat

@{b}ListFormat@{ub}

Purpose: Set the format for the Main List.

Syntax : ListFormat FORMAT/F

FORMAT/F - A set of MUI column format commands.
           For some reason only the Column format commands work.
           
           see @{b}List Format@{ub} in the @{"Config Window" link ConfigWindow}.
           
         
Example: listformat 'col=0,col=5,col=2'
         listformat ',,,'
         listformat ''
@endnode

@node RX_NoteDelete

@{b}NoteDelete@{ub}

Purpose: Delete the current entry's (active) external note data file.

Syntax : NoteDelete (no parameters)
 
Example: notedelete
@endnode

@node RX_NoteEdit

@{b}NoteEdit@{ub}

Purpose: Invoke the chosen editor (in configuration) to edit the current (active) entry's external note data file.

Syntax : NoteEdit (no parameters)
 
Example: noteedit
@endnode

@node RX_NoteExamine

@{b}NoteExamine@{ub}

Purpose: Reload the current (active) entry's external note data file.
         This is only useful if the Note Window is open.

Syntax : NoteExamine (no parameters)
 
Example: noteexamine
@endnode

@node RX_NoteScan

@{b}Scan@{ub}

Purpose: NoteScan the current External Notes drawer for note files.

Syntax : NoteScan (no parameters)
 
Example: notescan
@endnode

@node RX_NoteView

@{b}NoteView@{ub}

Purpose: Open and close the external note view window.

Syntax : NoteView STATE/N

STATE/N  - A value of 0 will close the window, whereas any other value will open it. Without this parameter value will toggle.

Example: noteview state 1
@endnode

@node RX_Open

@{b}Open@{ub}

Purpose: Load a Locate data file.

Syntax : Open FILE,MERGE/S

FILE    - Full name and path of the file to be loaded.
MERGE/S - Flag to cause @{"Merge-Loading" link Merging}.

Example: open ram:YourAddresses.loc merge
@endnode

@node RX_PhoneActive

@{b}PhoneActive@{ub}  ENTRY/N

Purpose: To activate of of the entries in the Phone List.

Syntax : PhoneActive ENTRY/N

ENTRY/N - The number of the pop-list entry to select [1...4].

Example: phoneactive 2

The 'Phone:' data-field will now show the contents of the active entry in the pop-list.
@endnode

@node RX_Remove

@{b}Remove@{ub}

Purpose: Remove all currently selected entries (or single Active) from list.

Syntax : Remove ACTIVE/S

ACTIVE/S - Switch to cause only active entry to be removed. Otherwise ALL the SELECTED entries are removed

Example: remove

         returns the number of entries removed.
@endnode

@node RX_Requester

@{b}Requester@{ub}

Purpose: Display a configurable requester for information or request purposes.
         It returns a number indicating which button was pressed. The actual numbering of the buttons is 1, 2, ..., n, 0.

Syntax : Requester TITLE/K,BUTTON/K,MESSAGE/F
 
Example: requester "This is a message."
         requester title "A User Message" button "Fine" "This is just to say hello"
         requester title "A Question" button "*_Amiga|_pc" "What computer do you like?"
            answer = result /* "Amiga" would return 1, "pc" would return 0 */
@endnode

@node RX_RX

@{b}RX@{ub}

Purpose: Invoke an ARexx script from within Alarmist. Meaning that the script's host address is set to "Locate.x".

Syntax : RX FILE

FILE - Full name of the file to be executed.

Example: rx 'rexx:test_script.rexx'
@endnode

@node RX_Save

@{b}Save@{ub}

Purpose: Save the list using the current filename.

Syntax : Save (no parameters)
 
Example: save
@endnode

@node RX_SaveAs

@{b}SaveAs@{ub}

Purpose: Save the list using a specified filename.

Syntax : SaveAs FILE,REQUEST/S

FILE      - The new file name.
REQUEST/S - Flag to cause a file requester to appear.

Example: saveas ram:test request
@endnode

@node RX_Search

@{b}Search@{ub}

Purpose: @{"Search" link Searching} for a string in the contents of the list.
         If a match is found then this list entry will become active.

Syntax : Search CASESENS/S,FIELD/N/K,STRING/F/A

CASESENS/S - Flag to cause a case sensitive (exact case matching) search.
FIELD/N/K  - Number to indicate what field(s) to search.
             The field numbering matches that used in the @{"GetField" link RX_GetField} ARexx command above, but if you wish to include all fields in the search then specify a number of 0.
STRING/F/A - An AmigaDOS search pattern.

Example: search Wils#? casesens field 1
         search Wilson field 0
@endnode

@node RX_Select

@{b}Select@{ub}

Purpose: Cause an entry in the list to become selected (does not activate it).

Syntax : Select ENTRY/N,NOSELECT/S,ALL/S

ENTRY/N    - Number of the entry in the list to select.
NOSELECT/S - Flag to deselect ALL entries in the list.
ALL/S      - Flag to select ALL entries in the list.

Example: select 10
         select noselect
@endnode

@node RX_SetField

@{b}SetField@{ub}

Purpose: Put the supplied text string into a field.
         This also simulates the effect of pressing return afterwards.

Syntax : SetField NUMBER/N,VALUE/F/A

NUMBER/N   - The field to act on.

The following are the field numbers (using the default names for the fields):

  1 - Last Name
  2 - First Name
  3 - Street
  4 - Suburb
  5 - Post Code
  6 - Phone (Change the phone entry number using the @{"PhoneActive" link RX_PhoneActive} command)
  7 - Notes (is *not* the external note file!)

VALUE/F/A - The string to put in the specified field.
             You should use this argument(s) last and use the command 'VALUE' before hand.
             The rest of the line after the command is used as the string, so spaces are allowed.

Example: 'setfield 3 value=new street'

This is the standard way of entering Event data via ARexx.
If you wish to insert a new Event then just deselect the list with the 'active noactive' command then proceed to insert data into the fields with the 'putfield' command.
@endnode

